That's my first instinct too, but just to stir up trouble...

It's Evil to kill a random Evil devil worshipper to free a trapped soul,
but is it Evil to kill a devil worshipper because he is a devil
worshipper? Because I can easily imagine a setup where the party of LG
inquisitors goes around rooting out Evil devil worshippers with no
ulterior motive, and I'd expect less people would claim that is Evil
than this soul freeing business. Is this more Evil because there's an
ulterior motive? Or less because you're actually helping an innocent
third party?

What if you keep an eye on the devil worshippers until they try to do
something nasty like sacrificing virgins or poisoning water supplies and
then kill them while they're "resisting arrest"? Without the wider
context with the trapped soul, I don't think anyone would claim that is
Evil, since this is the absolute staple of D&amp;D: bad guys do bad things,
good guys kill them and take their stuff. But deliberatly waiting for
someone to give you a justification to kill them... is that really
better than just killing them outright?

Yep, sounds like "screw the paladin" to me too. :)

I guess what's causing the cognitive dissonance it that this is just not
the way the metaphysics usually works in D&amp;D: sacrifice of semi-random
intelligent creatures typically generates energy to accomplish Evil
goals, not Good goals. (I'm assuming that that the soul is an innocent
unfairly trapped, not some sort of fiendish entity.)

