I'm reminded of a time when I played a paladin for a new campaign in a
country where slavery was legal.  Two clergy were "mistakenly" taken
as slaves, and I was sent to find them and release them - my mcguffin
for the campaign.

As a reason for the party to get together, we all had reasons to seek
a sage who could help us on our quests.  While I had an independent
lead to my quest of questioning the slave auctioneer, I had to wait
until the next slave auction.  This sage knew where the clergy were
now.  He was willing to sell me the information for 5,000gp.  I was a
1st level paladin who had to borrow 100gp from the church to book a
boat passage to meet this sage.  Not bloody likely.  He gave a similar
outrageous cost to all the PCs.

Later, he gathered us all together and offered an alternative.  He
once had a "Book of Evil" which was taken from him by some evil
wizard.  The wizard was out of town.  If the party were to get the
book from his house and bring it back to him, he would tell us what we
wanted to know.  When I asked the sage what the wizard wanted th ebook
for, all he said was "to do evil".  I kept quiet as the party
discussed what to do.  We had to figure out how to sneak around the
city, break into the house to burglarize it, try to stay away from the
town watch, bring the book back to the sage, then get out of Dodge to
avoid arrest.

I'm sitting there thinking.  This sage has the information I need to
help free two of my church's clergy.  For that information, he either
wants me to pay him 5,000gp or commit several acts of breaking the
law.  The country may be allowing slavery, but a law against burglary
is reasonable.  I at least had some potential lead.  I said "Your
price is too high" and left the sage's house.  I had no original
intention of ratting out the party anyway, but one did ask for my word
I wouldn't and I gave it.

The rest of the party carried out their burglary and got the book.  I
just sat there listening them do it.  They did have to fight some
skeletons, so the wizard who took the book was evil, but I didn't
regret my decision.  The sage rewarded them with a ledger that had the
information everyone needed for their own quests, most likely
everything was related somehow.  For metagame sake of the game the
party invited me back in to use the ledger and work together as a
party.

Gerald Katz
