Why is worshipping a devil evil per se?
(beside the arguments presented in the Book of Vile Darkness)
What were the tales of the characters' parents in their youth. Did
they tell them of the good devils, the good deeds of devils? No (I
hope). If the characters aren't all Kaspar Hausers, they learned that
devils are evil, that no good can come from a devil. In a D&amp;D world
evil is tangible, physical. Evil has a face, when it comes to evil
outsiders. The bedtime story can actually rip your heart out and
devour your soul. This aspect should frighten the hell (hehe) out of
the characters.

A devil is evil incarnate. It cannot repent. It cannot change its
ways. It is always lawful evil. That is a game mechanic.

People (humans and other mortals) have a free will. People can repent.
They can change their behaviour. Though most people would rate
themselves as lawful good, they are usually neutral (more than 50%).
So most people wouldn't act on devil worshippers in their backyard. A
good character won't stand this, because it learned early on that
devils are evil. What would a character think of a person who consorts
with fiends? If such a person can be swayed to see their wrongs, good.
If it can't be swayed, it is a menace to the society, to the lives and
souls of everyone and it must be dealt with (which means killed,
imprisoned or driven off). Can a good character stand by and watch? A
good character hopes for the redemption of wrong-doers and will give
the devil worshippers a chance to step aside.

When it comes to gods, it gets more complex. Gods don't have a fixed
alignment, they can change. A gods alignment isn't a game mechanic,
though it usually stays the same. In the D&amp;D multiverse this aspect is
expressed in the shifts of godly planes. Hell and heaven don't shift,
they are static (a metagame concept, a game mechanic). Devoted
followers of evil gods are usually evil themselves. What can a
character expect from a follower of a particular evil god? This
question is answered by the cultural background of the region the
characters act in. If the characters know that the followers of a
particular deity usually kill people, summon undead and commit other
atrocities, they would show a neutral behaviour, if the wouldn't act
on their knowledge. Have you ever wondered why evil temples tend to be
underground and not next to a temple devoted to a good deity? Mmh,
maybe you play it in another way.

So if you present the worship of devils as normal for the region and
you sell the actions of the cult as not evil, where has the paladin
come from? Not from that region is my guess. On what believes is
lawful good founded in your campaign?
