Your scenario is not Lawful and that counts too. Also, if your paladin is
not careful, he's setting himself up for an altercation with factions in the
city who are also Lawful Good but have been called to the temple in order to
quell a disturbance. Being wilfully negligent of risks to alignment ought to
count against the alignment.

This school of "thought" is likely common to the city: "I'm friends with a
few Asmodeus worshippers. I don't exactly know what in Asmodeus's holy book,
given that it's written in a language I haven't bothered to learn, but the
worshippers are always nice to me. That proves that Asmodeus worship isn't
an evil religion!" Besides the useful idiots, the average Joe in the city is
a moderate who just wants to be left alone. He'll side with them until given
a reason to do otherwise.

The paladin is Good and cannot ignore the cult, but he is also Lawful and
cannot raid its outposts in the city. The best he can do, without cover of
law, is to gather evidence. Besides it's the smart thing to do; if he sneaks
into the temple then some poor sod who is just trying to sleep without
hearing lightning bolts cracking next door is going to call the guard.

But if you're on a mission from someone in the city government, then the
guard won't get involved. This requires finding out what actions are
allowable. If factions in the government don't want the temple disturbed,
then the intrustion will have to be a stealth mission. Think "James Bond".

